ğŸ” JavaScript Strict Mode

What is Strict Mode?

**Strict Mode** helps write **safer and cleaner JavaScript** by catching common mistakes.

```js
"use strict";
```

ğŸ“Œ Must be at the **top of file or function**

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âœ… Benefits of Strict Mode

* Prevents undeclared variables
* Throws errors instead of silent failures
* Improves code quality
* Makes debugging easier

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âŒ Without Strict Mode

```js
x = 10; // No error (bad practice)
```

---

âœ… With Strict Mode

```js
"use strict";
x = 10; // Error âŒ
```

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸš¨ JavaScript Error Handling

What is Error Handling?

Error handling allows programs to **handle unexpected errors gracefully** without crashing.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ”„ try...catch Block

```js
try {
  let result = x / y;
  console.log(result);
} catch (error) {
  console.log("Error occurred:", error.message);
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Prevents app crash

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ” finally Block

Runs **always**, whether error occurs or not.

```js
try {
  console.log("Try block");
} catch (e) {
  console.log("Catch block");
} finally {
  console.log("Always runs");
}
```

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§¾ Error Object

Common properties:

* `error.name`
* `error.message`
* `error.stack`

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âœ‹ Throwing Custom Errors

```js
let age = 15;

if (age < 18) {
  throw new Error("Age must be 18+");
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Useful for validation

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ§  Error Handling with Async/Await

```js
async function fetchData() {
  try {
    let res = await fetch(url);
  } catch (error) {
    console.log("Fetch failed");
  }
}
```

ğŸ“Œ Always use `try-catch` with async code

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ†š try-catch vs if-else

| try-catch              | if-else            |
| ---------------------- | ------------------ |
| Handles runtime errors | Handles conditions |
| Cleaner for errors     | Not for exceptions |
| Used in async code     | Used in logic      |

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

âŒ Common Debugging Mistakes

* Ignoring console errors
* Too many console.logs
* Not using breakpoints
* Catching errors but not handling them

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

ğŸ’¡ Best Practices

* Use `console.log` smartly
* Enable strict mode
* Always handle errors
* Write readable code
* Remove debug logs before production

